{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "PR Review — Per-user BYOK LLM credentials",
  "description": "Walkthrough of the bring-your-own-key (BYOK) change set: how a user's own provider key is resolved once and threaded through every classify/judge path so their load bills their key, while keyless users fall through to the shared env key unchanged. Reviewer arc: contract → totality guarantee → fall-through seam → the five callers → the createCompletion sink → prod config → the tests that lock it.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "packages/api/src/__tests__/byok-credentials.test.ts",
      "line": 1,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 1, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 15, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "1 · What this PR promises",
      "description": "Situation: the contract header for the whole change. Mechanism: the high-traffic classify/judge paths (firewall judge, classify-tool, summarize, naver, github) each resolve a user's provider key via getUserLlmCredentials() and pass it down to createCompletion(). Implication for the reviewer: there are two behaviors to verify across every caller — (a) a user with a key bills THEIR key, and (b) a keyless user is byte-for-byte the old env-key path. Gotcha: this is purely a routing/billing change — no classification logic moves, so the review burden is 'did the credential thread reach the sink, and is the keyless path untouched.'"
    },
    {
      "file": "packages/api/src/llm-credentials.ts",
      "line": 40,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 31, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 56, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "2 · The resolver — TOTAL by design",
      "description": "Situation: the one function every caller depends on. Mechanism: getUserLlmCredentials looks up the user, decrypts their stored keys, and tags the result with quotaScope=userId. Implication: it is awaited on the firewall hot path and inside batch loops, so it MUST NOT throw — a throw would abort a whole sweep, not one email. The DB lookup is wrapped (lines 42-48): on failure it logs + captures and returns {} (shared-env fallback) instead of propagating. Gotcha: console.warn comes before captureError on purpose — captureError is a silent no-op without a Sentry DSN, so the console line is the only guaranteed signal (the repo's hard rule: never swallow without a console signal)."
    },
    {
      "file": "packages/api/src/llm-credentials.ts",
      "line": 21,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 11, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 29, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "3 · safeDecrypt — degrade per key, don't die",
      "description": "Situation: the second failure mode. Mechanism: decryptOptional throws deterministically on a corrupt or pre-v1 ciphertext; safeDecrypt catches that, signals (console + capture, scope byok.decrypt), and returns null for THAT key only. Implication: a single rotted key degrades to the env key — it does not strand the user's other key or every future email. Gotcha: returning null (not re-throwing, not {}) is what lets getProviderChain treat the key as 'absent' and fall through — verify this null is the same shape a keyless user produces, because that equivalence is the entire safety argument."
    },
    {
      "file": "packages/api/src/providers/index.ts",
      "line": 272,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 272, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 298, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "4 · The fall-through seam",
      "description": "Situation: where credentials become a provider chain. Mechanism: getProviderChain builds user providers ONLY from explicitly supplied keys (openRouterApiKey/geminiApiKey/openAiApiKey); a null/absent key contributes nothing. Implication: this is why a keyless user — or a user whose key just degraded to null in step 3 — produces the exact same chain as before the PR. Gotcha: note the playgroundOnly branch (295-297) fails CLOSED so a public visitor can never reach the env key — that's a different, pre-existing path; this PR's BYOK callers never set playgroundOnly, so they keep the env provider as the tail of the chain."
    },
    {
      "file": "packages/api/src/email-firewall.ts",
      "line": 171,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 171, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 197, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "5 · Caller #1 (hot path) — judgeAndMirrorEmail",
      "description": "Situation: the firewall's per-email judge entry point. Mechanism: a new optional `credentials` param. When a caller already resolved them (the backfill sweep, step 6), they're reused; otherwise line 183 resolves them itself: `credentials ?? (await getUserLlmCredentials(userId))`. Implication: a keyless user resolves to {} → no keys → env provider, so this is a verified no-op for them. Gotcha: the optional param is the key design choice — single-email callers pay one lookup, batch callers pay zero per email. Confirm the param is truly optional everywhere so no existing caller broke."
    },
    {
      "file": "packages/api/src/email-firewall.ts",
      "line": 368,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 365, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 380, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "6 · Resolve-once: the backfill sweep",
      "description": "Situation: the canonical batch pattern this PR repeats five times. Mechanism: backfillEmailAttentionItems resolves the user's credentials ONCE (line 371) before the loop, then passes them into every judgeAndMirrorEmail call. Implication: a backlog can be hundreds of emails for one user — per-email resolution would mean hundreds of identical DB queries. Gotcha: this is the rationale comment every other caller points back to with 'see judgeAndMirrorEmail.' Reviewer check: the resolve sits OUTSIDE the loop and the loop's per-email try/catch still isolates failures (a resolver that already can't throw makes this airtight)."
    },
    {
      "file": "packages/api/src/naver-imap.ts",
      "line": 158,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 155, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 163, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "7 · Callers #2–#4 — naver / github / summarize (same shape)",
      "description": "Situation: the resolve-once pattern applied to the other batch surfaces. Mechanism: naver-imap resolves llmCredentials once per poll (line 161) and threads it into each judgeAndMirrorEmail; github-source does the same per ingest batch (github-source.ts:120); email-summarize resolves once per batch (email-summarize.ts:78). Implication: every recurring per-user sweep now bills the user's key with exactly one extra query per sweep. Gotcha: confirm each resolve is hoisted above its loop like here — a resolve accidentally left inside the loop would silently reintroduce the per-row query cost the pattern exists to avoid."
    },
    {
      "file": "packages/api/src/gmail.ts",
      "line": 868,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 868, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 884, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "8 · Caller #5 — the classify-tool path",
      "description": "Situation: the user-initiated classify call (not a background sweep). Mechanism: classifyEmails resolves credentials (line 874) and forwards them into classifyEmailBatch alongside userId. Implication: an interactive 'classify my inbox' run also bills the user's own key. Gotcha: this is the one path where userId AND credentials both matter — userId still flows for cost accounting/quota even when the user's own key pays, so the per-user daily cost cap still applies. The byok test (byok-credentials.test.ts:72) asserts exactly this: credentials present, userId still 'user-123'."
    },
    {
      "file": "packages/api/src/poc-judge.ts",
      "line": 391,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 391, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 398, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "9 · The library seam — judgeEmail",
      "description": "Situation: the shared judge entry every caller funnels into. Mechanism: `credentials` is a new optional positional (4th) param, passed straight through extractWithDial → createCompletion. Implication: keeping it positional-and-optional means existing 2-arg callers (judgeEmail(email, userId)) keep working untouched. Gotcha: positional growth is a smell to flag — judgeEmail now takes 6 params (email, userId, context, credentials, modelOverride, onLlmError). It's threaded correctly here, but note for the review whether an options object would age better than continuing to append positionals."
    },
    {
      "file": "packages/api/src/openai.ts",
      "line": 217,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 206, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 218, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "10 · The sink — createCompletion → getProviderChain",
      "description": "Situation: where the thread finally terminates. Mechanism: createCompletion reads options.credentials and hands them to getProviderChain (line 217), producing the user-key-first chain from step 4. Implication: every BYOK caller's whole job is just to get a populated `credentials` onto this options object — once here, routing and the env fall-through are handled by code that predates the PR. Gotcha: options.credentials is undefined for the keyless path, so getProviderChain() defaults to {} → identical chain. This undefined-vs-populated split is precisely what the threading tests assert at the two seams (classifyEmailBatch and judgeEmail)."
    },
    {
      "file": "render.yaml",
      "line": 32,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 32, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 50, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "11 · Prod config — model pins + the billing rationale",
      "description": "Situation: the ops half of the change. Mechanism: CHAT/AGENT/JUDGE/VISION models are pinned to a funded paid flash model; FALLBACK_MODEL stays :free on purpose. Implication: prod unifies user-facing surfaces on the reliable paid model, per-user load bills each user's own key (the BYOK code above), and DAILY_COST_CAP_CENTS backstops the shared key. The :free fallback is the $0 degradation net that only activates on 402 (credit exhausted) so the service degrades instead of hard-failing. Gotcha: model names are public, not secrets, so pinning them in-repo is fine — but confirm these IDs exist on the funded gateway's catalog, since a renamed/missing SKU here fails every surface at once."
    },
    {
      "file": "packages/api/src/__tests__/llm-credentials.test.ts",
      "line": 59,
      "selection": { "start": { "line": 54, "character": 0 }, "end": { "line": 93, "character": 0 } },
      "title": "12 · The tests that lock totality + threading",
      "description": "Situation: the two specs that guard the whole PR. Mechanism: llm-credentials.test.ts proves the resolver is TOTAL — DB failure degrades to {} (line 59), a corrupt key degrades to null while preserving the other key (line 71), and both emit a capture signal. byok-credentials.test.ts proves the THREADING — credentials reach createCompletion's options when supplied, and are absent (undefined) when not. Implication: together they pin both invariants a reviewer would otherwise have to trace by hand across six files. Gotcha: the threading tests assert at the two library seams (classifyEmailBatch, judgeEmail) rather than each of the five callers — so a future caller that forgets to thread credentials would NOT be caught here. Worth flagging as the coverage edge."
    },
    {
      "title": "Next Steps",
      "description": "You can now review this change as a single claim: 'a user's key is resolved once per sweep, threaded through the judge/classify seams to getProviderChain, and a keyless or degraded key is byte-identical to the pre-PR env path.' Open questions surfaced for the review: (1) judgeEmail's growing positional signature (step 9), (2) threading tests assert at seams, not per-caller (step 12), (3) render.yaml model IDs must exist on the funded gateway (step 11). The code-review pass that follows should adjudicate these three plus scan for any caller that resolves credentials inside a loop instead of above it."
    }
  ]
}
